{
  "doc_id": "5130",
  "text": "Additionally, we found that EGFR was overexpressed in prostate cancer cells and that high EGFR-expressing cells preferentially formed prostaspheres. The knockdown of HER2 in C4-2B cells did not affect the levels of EGFR expression. Our attempts to knockdown EGFR were lethal to prostate cancer cells which is not surprising as these lethal EGFR knockdowns have been observed in a number of studies [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Taken together this suggests that EGFR may function in various aspects of prostate cancer progression including tumor maintenance and self-renewal. Several lines of evidence support this view, including the previous observations that the addition of EGF to defined media promotes stem cell maintenance [CITATION_4] and that the activation of EGFR increases prostasphere formation [CITATION_5] .",
